// Basic HTTP request and response
// Shows two styles for making a request:
//   1. Declare a named request variable, then chain methods and call .do().
//   2. Declare the request inline inside a response(...) initializer.
//
// response exposes .body(), .status(), .ok(), .duration(), and more.

// Style 1: named request variable — useful when you need to reuse or
// configure the request across multiple lines before executing it.
def r as request(GET)

def res as response(
  r.path("https://google.com").do()
)

print(res.body())
print(res.status())

assert(res.status() == 200)

// Style 2: assign .do() directly to a string — coerces to the response body.
// Useful when only the body text is needed and status/headers can be ignored.
def response_body as string()

def r2 as request(GET)

r2.path("https://google.com")

response_body = r2.do()

def status as integer(r2.status())

print(response_body)
print(status)
